{"title_page": "Vice-Admiral of the Blue", "text_new": "{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of the Blue 1702 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of Blue (1624-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the Blue\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAB \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Vice-admiral of the White]] \n| lower rank     =  [[Rear-admiral of the red]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the Blue''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the White (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals. From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence sixth; after 1805 it was the seventh. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank. The [[command flag]] for an Vice-Admiral of the Blue is pictured opposite.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. In 1688 the official rank of [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] was formally introduced<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the Blue was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the White (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%20the%20ranks%20of%20rear%20admiral%2C%20vice%20admiral%20and%20admiral%20of%20the%20fleet%20are%20sometimes%20considered%20generically%20to%20be%20admirals&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence sixth; after 1805 it was the seventh. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank..<ref>{{cite web |last1=Services |first1=Library |title=Information sheet no 055 Squadron colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Order of precedence Admirals of the Colour==\nThe Navy was divided into three squadrons Red, White and Blue in order of seniority. Admirals were appointed to these squadrons and therefore their rank and squadron split the seniority originally into 9 bands then later 10 with \u2018Admiral of the Fleet' as senior to all others.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1805 to 1864:\n# [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n# [[Admiral of the Red|Admiral of the Red Squadron]] (rank created in 1805)\n# [[Admiral of the White|Admiral of the White Squadron]] \n# [[Admiral of the Blue|Admiral of the Blue Squadron]] \n# [[Vice-admiral of the red|Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron]] \n# [[Vice-admiral of the White|Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron'''\n# [[Rear-admiral of the red|Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the White|Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the Blue|Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1688 to 1805:\n# Admiral of the Fleet, (rank created in 1688)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron'''\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nAdmirals without an appointment were colloquially referred to as Yellow Admirals. Ships of the Royal Navy flew the Ensign that coincided with the squadron of their commanding officer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of command flags of the Royal Navy]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military ranks of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy appointments]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of the Blue 1702 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of Blue (1624-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the Blue\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAB \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Vice-admiral of the White]] \n| lower rank     =  [[Rear-admiral of the red]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the Blue''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the White (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals. From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence sixth; after 1805 it was the seventh. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank. The [[command flag]] for an Vice-Admiral of the Blue is pictured opposite.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. In 1688 the official rank of [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] was formally introduced<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the Blue was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the White (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%