{"title_page": "Jayanath Colombage", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  = [[Admiral]], [[Professor]]\n|name              = Jayanath Colombage\n|honorific_suffix  = [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], rcds, psc MSc (DS), MA (IS), Dip in IR, Dip in CR, FNI (Lond)\n|native_name       =\n|native_name_lang  =\n|image         = http://navy.lk/assets/images/commander/past_commanders/adm_jsk_colombage.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|10|14}}\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n|birth_place   =\n|death_place   =\n|placeofburial =\n|placeofburial_label =\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      =\n|birth_name    =\n|allegiance    = Sri Lanka\n|branch        = Executive\n|serviceyears  =1978-2014\n|rank          =[[Admiral]]\n|servicenumber = NRX 0135<ref name=\"chart\">{{cite news|title=Travis Sinniah to have shortest tenure?|url=http://www.srilankamirror.com/news/5106-travis-sinniah-to-have-shortest-tenure|accessdate=25 October 2017|agency=Sri Lanka Mirror|publisher=srilankamirror.com|date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n|unit          =\n|commands      =[[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]]\n|battles       =[[Sri Lankan Civil War]]\n|battles_label =\n|awards        = [[ File:Rana Sura Padakkama bar.GIF|20px]] [[Rana Sura Padakkama]]<br> [[File: Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya bar.GIF|20px]] [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]<br> [[File: Uttama Seva Padakkama Bar.gif|20px]] [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n|memorials     =\n|spouse        = Srima Colombage\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =\n|signature     =\n|website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|module        =\n}}\nAdmiral Professor '''Jayanath Colombage''' RSP, VSV, USP, rcds, psc MSc (DS), MA (IS), Dip in IR, Dip in CR, FNI (Lond) is the 18th [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/120930/news/new-navy-chief-is-rear-admiral-colombage-14668.html|title=New Navy Chief is Rear Admiral Colombage|date=30 September 2012|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=Past>{{cite web|title=Past Commanders |url=http://www.navy.lk/past-commanders.html |publisher=navy.lk |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902032132/http://www.navy.lk/past-commanders.html |archivedate= 2 September 2014 }}</ref> Published author of title <nowiki>''Asymmetric Warfare a Sea''</nowiki>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morebooks.de/store/gb/book/asymmetric-warfare-at-sea/isbn/978-3-659-86575-6|title=Asymmetric Warfare at Sea|last=Colombage|first=Jayanath|date=2016-04-04|website=MoreBooks!|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> and currently is in advisory of Sea and Coast \"monthly maritime magazine\" http://www.seaandcoast.in/advisory\n\n== Education ==\nColombage was a student of [[St. Sylvester's College|St. Sylvester\u2019s College]], [[Kandy]], and became the first [[Alumni of St. Sylvester's College|old Sylvestrian]] to be elevated to the position of a Service Commander in the military history of Sri Lanka.\n\nHe was a promising National-Level athlete and undoubtedly the best all-round athlete of the college during his era. He was College Athletics Captain for 3 successive years from 1976 to 1978 and emerged Champion Athlete at the then Public Schools Meets. He was awarded College Colours as well as Sri Lanka Schools Colours for athletics.\n\nThough, his forte was track and field, he rose to become a Senior Prefect of the College and Lance Sergeant of the College Cadet Platoon. He was also a popular member of the College Band and took a keen interest in the activities of numerous societies and won the admiration of his peers as well as teachers.\n\n== Military career ==\nAdmiral Colombage joined the Sri Lanka Navy as an Officer Cadet in 1978 and successfully completed his basic training at the renowned [[Naval and Maritime Academy]] in [[Trincomalee]] winning the \u2018Sword of Honour\u2019 for the Best Officer Cadet of the 7th Intake. He was then selected to attend the prestigious International Midshipmen Course in the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]], Dartmouth in the United Kingdom.\n\nAdmiral Colombage is the second officer to be considered to the highest seat of the Commander of the Navy straight from an Operational Naval Command. He served as the Commander Eastern Naval Area at the historic Naval Dockyard in Trincomalee until he was chosen to steer the Sri Lanka Navy. He has achieved many firsts in his distinguished, decorative and unblemished naval career spanning 34 years. He has been conferred with two master's degrees - Master of Science in Defence Studies and Master of Arts in International Studies. Presently, Vice Admiral Colombage is reading for his Doctorate in Philosophy.\n\nAdmiral Colombage has been a regular lecturer at the Defence Services Command and Staff College in Colombo since its inception. He is an expert in Maritime Security and has published papers and conducted National-Level Seminars on Maritime Security. He has been certified by the International Maritime Organization as a lecturer in International Conventions on Port and Ship Security. He has presented scores of papers on Maritime Terrorism related subjects in Sri Lanka as well as at international forums. He has published a book titled \u2018Naval Terms and Expressions\u2019 and actively contributes to various academic forums.\n\nHe is a distinguished alumnus of the Defence Services Staff College, Wellington in India, Asia Pacific Center for Security Studies, Hawaii in the United States of America and Royal College of Defence Studies in the United Kingdom. He is also a Fellow of the Nautical Institute of the United Kingdom and currently the Chairman of the Sri Lanka Branch. He holds Diplomas in Security Studies, Conflict Resolution, International Affairs and Information Technology.\n\nHe has commanded four Operational Naval Commands, namely, Eastern, Northern, Western and North Central, for a period of over 5 years. He served twice as the Director General Operations at Naval Headquarters. Prior to that, he served as the Director General Services as well as the Director Naval Training and Personnel. He has also served in the appointments of Deputy Area Commander (North Central), Deputy Area Commander (South) and Deputy Area Commander (East).\n\nAdmiral Colombage has commanded numerous ships of the Sri Lanka Navy including the Fast Missile Vessels, Fast Gun Boats, Fast Attack Craft and amphibious ships and has been awarded the Surface Warfare Badge. He is a weapon specialist who has undergone extensive training with the Indian Navy and in the People\u2019s Republic of China.\n\nHe is a recipient of the Rana Sura Padakkama for gallantry. Among the other medals awarded to him are the Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya, the Utthama Seva Padakkama, the Sri Lanka Navy 50th Anniversary Medal, the Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal, the President\u2019s Inauguration Medal, the 50th Independence Anniversary Commemoration Medal, the East Humanitarian Operation Medal, the North Humanitarian Operation Medal, the North and East Operations Medal, the Purna Bhumi Padakkama, the Vadamarachchi Operation Medal and the Riviresa Campaign Service Medal.\n\nAdmiral Colombage is the most commended Naval Officer. Successive Commanders of the Navy have issued him with \u2018Letters of Commendation\u2019 for exceptional execution of duties and responsibilities and for his achievements in numerous fields such as operational activities, leadership, managerial and administrative skills, academic achievements, highest commitment and dedication towards the cause of the nation. He is the recipient of the prestigious 5-Star Commendation Badge.\n\nHe aptly showed his prowess as an athlete even after joining the Navy winning the Sri Lanka Navy Colours. He held the post of President of the Sri Lanka Navy Athletics Club from 1999 to 2006 and also served as President of the renowned Ceylonese Track and Field Club. Presently, he is the President of the Sri Lanka Navy Sports Board and a Vice President of the Defence Services Sports Board.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[D. W. A. S. Dissanayake]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]]|years=2012-2014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jayantha Perera]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Navy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colombage, Jayanath}}\n[[Category:Sri Lankan admirals]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Navy]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Naval and Maritime Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St. Sylvester's College]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  = [[Admiral]], [[Professor]]\n|name              = Jayanath Colombage\n|honorific_suffix  = [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], rcds, psc MSc (DS), MA (IS), Dip in IR, Dip in CR, FNI (Lond)\n|native_name       =\n|native_name_lang  =\n|image         = http://navy.lk/assets/images/commander/past_commanders/adm_jsk_colombage.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|10|14}}\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n|birth_place   =\n|death_place   =\n|placeofburial =\n|placeofburial_label =\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      =\n|birth_name    =\n|allegiance    = {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|branch        = Executive\n|serviceyears  =1978-2014\n|rank          =[[Admiral]]\n|servicenumber = NRX 0135<ref name=\"chart\">{{cite news|title=Travis Sinniah to have shortest tenure?|url=http://www.srilankamirror.com/news/5106-travis-sinniah-to-have-shortest-tenure|accessdate=25 October 2017|agency=Sri Lanka Mirror|publisher=srilankamirror.com|date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n|unit          =\n|commands      =[[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]]\n|battles       =[[Sri Lankan Civil War]]\n|battles_label =\n|awards        = [[ File:Rana Sura Padakkama bar.GIF|20px]] [[Rana Sura Padakkama]]<br> [[File: Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya bar.GIF|20px]] [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]<br> [[File: Uttama Seva Padakkama Bar.gif|20px]] [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n|memorials     =\n|spouse        = Srima Colombage\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =\n|signature     =\n|website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|module        =\n}}\nAdmiral Professor '''Jayanath Colombage''' RSP, VSV, USP, rcds, psc MSc (DS), MA (IS), Dip in IR, Dip in CR, FNI (Lond) is the 18th [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/120930/news/new-navy-chief-is-rear-admiral-colombage-14668.html|title=New Navy Chief is Rear Admiral Colombage|date=30 September 2012|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=Past>{{cite web|title=Past Commanders |url=http://www.navy.lk/past-commanders.html |publisher=navy.lk |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902032132/http://www.navy.lk/past-commanders.html |archivedate= 2 September 2014 }}</ref> Published author of title <nowiki>''Asymmetric Warfare a Sea''</nowiki>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morebooks.de/store/gb/book/asymmetric-warfare-at-sea/isbn/978-3-659-86575-6|title=Asymmetric Warfare at Sea|last=Colombage|first=Jayanath|date=2016-04-04|website=MoreBooks!|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> and currently is in advisory of Sea and Coast \"monthly maritime magazine\" http://www.seaandcoast.in/advisory\n\n== Education ==\nColombage was a student of [[St. Sylvester's College|St. Sylvester\u2019s College]], [[Kandy]], and became the first [[Alumni of St. Sylvester's College|old Sylvestrian]] to be elevated to the position of a Service Commander in the military history of Sri Lanka.\n\nHe was a promising National-Level athlete and undoubtedly the best all-round athlete of the college during his era. He was College Athletics Captain for 3 successive years from 1976 to 1978 and emerged Champion Athlete at the then Public Schools Meets. He was awarded College Colours as well as Sri Lanka Schools Colours for athletics.\n\nThough, his forte was track and field, he rose to become a Senior Prefect of the College and Lance Sergeant of the College Cadet Platoon. He was also a popular member of the College Band and took a keen interest in the activities of numerous societies and won the admiration of his peers as well as teachers.\n\n== Military career ==\nAdmiral Colombage joined the Sri Lanka Navy as an Officer Cadet in 1978 and successfully completed his basic training at the renowned [[Naval and Maritime Academy]] in [[Trincomalee]] winning the \u2018Sword of Honour\u2019 for the Best Officer Cadet of the 7th Intake. He was then selected to attend the prestigious International Midshipmen Course in the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]], Dartmouth in the United Kingdom.\n\nAdmiral Colombage is the second officer to be considered to the highest seat of the Commander of the Navy straight from an Operational Naval Command. He served as the Commander Eastern Naval Area at the historic Naval Dockyard in Trincomalee until he was chosen to steer the Sri Lanka Navy. He has achieved many firsts in his distinguished, decorative and unblemished naval career spanning 34 years. He has been conferred with two master's degrees - Master of Science in Defence Studies and Master of Arts in International Studies. Presently, Vice Admiral Colombage is reading for his Doctorate in Philosophy.\n\nAdmiral Colombage has been a regular lecturer at the Defence Services Command and Staff College in Colombo since its inception. He is an expert in Maritime Security and has published papers and conducted National-Level Seminars on Maritime Security. He has been certified by the International Maritime Organization as a lecturer in International Conventions on Port and Ship Security. He has presented scores of papers on Maritime Terrorism related subjects in Sri Lanka as well as at international forums. He has published a book titled \u2018Naval Terms and Expressions\u2019 and actively contributes to various academic forums.\n\nHe is a distinguished alumnus of the Defence Services Staff College, Wellington in India, Asia Pacific Center for Security Studies, Hawaii in the United States of America and Royal College of Defence Studies in the United Kingdom. He is also a Fellow of the Nautical Institute of the United Kingdom and currently the Chairman of the Sri Lanka Branch. He holds Diplomas in Security Studies, Conflict Resolution, International Affairs and Information Technology.\n\nHe has commanded four Operational Naval Commands, namely, Eastern, Northern, Western and North Central, for a period of over 5 years. He served twice as the Director General Operations at Naval Headquarters. Prior to that, he served as the Director General Services as well as the Director Naval Training and Personnel. He has also served in the appointments of Deputy Area Commander (North Central), Deputy Area Commander (South) and Deputy Area Commander (East).\n\nAdmiral Colombage has commanded numerous ships of the Sri Lanka Navy including the Fast Missile Vessels, Fast Gun Boats, Fast Attack Craft and amphibious ships and has been awarded the Surface Warfare Badge. He is a weapon specialist who has undergone extensive training with the Indian Navy and in the People\u2019s Republic of China.\n\nHe is a recipient of the Rana Sura Padakkama for gallantry. Among the other medals awarded to him are the Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya, the Utthama Seva Padakkama, the Sri Lanka Navy 50th Anniversary Medal, the Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal, the President\u2019s Inauguration Medal, the 50th Independence Anniversary Commemoration Medal, the East Humanitarian Operation Medal, the North Humanitarian Operation Medal, the North and East Operations Medal, the Purna Bhumi Padakkama, the Vadamarachchi Operation Medal and the Riviresa Campaign Service Medal.\n\nAdmiral Colombage is the most commended Naval Officer. Successive Commanders of the Navy have issued him with \u2018Letters of Commendation\u2019 for exceptional execution of duties and responsibilities and for his achievements in numerous fields such as operational activities, leadership, managerial and administrative skills, academic achievements, highest commitment and dedication towards the cause of the nation. He is the recipient of the prestigious 5-Star Commendation Badge.\n\nHe aptly showed his prowess as an athlete even after joining the Navy winning the Sri Lanka Navy Colours. He held the post of President of the Sri Lanka Navy Athletics Club from 1999 to 2006 and also served as President of the renowned Ceylonese Track and Field Club. Presently, he is the President of the Sri Lanka Navy Sports Board and a Vice President of the Defence Services Sports Board.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[D. W. A. S. Dissanayake]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]]|years=2012-2014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jayantha Perera]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Navy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colombage, Jayanath}}\n[[Category:Sri Lankan admirals]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Navy]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Naval and Maritime Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St. Sylvester's College]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove flagicon from infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jayanath_Colombage"}
{"title_page": "Tawny-crowned honeyeater", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Tawny crowned honeyeater Stowe.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[William John Swainson|Swainson]], 1837\n| taxon = Gliciphila melanops\n| authority = [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]] <small>1801</small>\n| synonyms = * ''Phylidonyris melanops''\n}}\n\nThe '''tawny-crowned honeyeater''' (''Gliciphila melanops'') is a [[passerine]] bird native to southern Australia.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe tawny-crowned honeyeater was originally described by ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1801 as ''Certhia melanops''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | page=xxxvi | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261410 }}</ref> Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] terms ''melano-'' 'black' and ''\u014dps'' 'face'.<ref name=Liddell1980>{{cite book | author = [[Henry George Liddell|Liddell, Henry George]] and [[Robert Scott (philologist)|Robert Scott]] | year = 1980 | title = [[A Greek-English Lexicon]] (Abridged Edition) | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = United Kingdom | isbn =0-19-910207-4}}</ref>\n\nIt was previously classified in the genus ''[[Phylidonyris]]'' but a recent molecular study has shown it to be more distantly related to members of that genus.<ref>Driskell, A.C., Christidis, L (2004) Phylogeny and evolution of the Australo-Papuan\nhoneyeaters (Passeriformes, Meliphagidae) ''Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution'' '''31''' 943\u2013960</ref> It was placed in the genus ''Gliciphila'' by [[Gregory Mathews]] in 1912, and this name was used in its current [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial]] name. [[DNA]] analysis has shown honeyeaters to be related to the [[Pardalotidae]] (pardalotes), [[Acanthizidae]] (Australian warblers, scrubwrens, thornbills, etc.), and [[Maluridae]] (Australian fairy-wrens) in a large [[Meliphagoidea]] superfamily.<ref>Barker, F.K., Cibois, A., Schikler, P., Feinstein, J., and Cracraft, J (2004) Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation. ''Proceedings Natl. Acad. Sci., USA'' '''101''' 11040-11045</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe tawny-crowned honeyeater is found from the [[Northern Rivers|North Coast]] of New South Wales through to the [[Eyre Peninsula]] in South Australia, as well as in Victoria and Tasmania. It also occurs in southwest Western Australia from [[Israelite Bay, Western Australia|Israelite Bay]] westwards. Its natural habitat is low shrubland and heath.<ref name=Ber93/>\n\n==Breeding==\nThe breeding season may take place from June to December. The bulky [[cup nest|cup-shaped nest]] is made of bark, grass, and even seaweed, and lined with softer material such as fur or wool. It is hidden among shrubby vegetation. The [[avian clutch size|clutch size]] is usually two or three, and occasionally four. Measuring 21 x 14&nbsp;mm, the oval eggs are beige, with buff or pink-tinged splotches.<ref name=Ber93>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = G  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | pages = 324 |isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"240\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Tawny-crowned honeyeater.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q775477}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, tawny-crowned}}\n[[Category:Meliphagidae|tawny-crowned honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1837|tawny-crowned honeyeater]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Tawny crowned honeyeater Stowe.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[William John Swainson|Swainson]], 1837\n| taxon = Gliciphila melanops\n| authority = [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]] <small>1801</small>\n| synonyms = * ''Phylidonyris melanops''\n}}\n\nThe '''tawny-crowned honeyeater''' (''Gliciphila melanops'') is a [[passerine]] bird native to southern Australia.\n\nThe tawny-crowned honeyeater was originally described by ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1801 as ''Certhia melanops''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | page=xxxvi | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261410 }}</ref> Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] terms ''melano-'' 'black' and ''\u014dps'' 'face'.<ref name=Liddell1980>{{cite book | author = [[Henry George Liddell|Liddell, Henry George]] and [[Robert Scott (philologist)|Robert Scott]] | year = 1980 | title = [[A Greek-English Lexicon]] (Abridged Edition) | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = United Kingdom | isbn =0-19-910207-4}}</ref>\n\nIt was previously classified in the genus ''[[Phylidonyris]]'' but a recent molecular study has shown it to be more distantly related to members of that genus.<ref>Driskell, A.C., Christidis, L (2004) Phylogeny and evolution of the Australo-Papuan\nhoneyeaters (Passeriformes, Meliphagidae) ''Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution'' '''31''' 943\u2013960</ref> It was placed in the genus ''Gliciphila'' by [[Gregory Mathews]] in 1912, and this name was used in its current [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial]] name. [[DNA]] analysis has shown honeyeaters to be related to the [[Pardalotidae]] (pardalotes), [[Acanthizidae]] (Australian warblers, scrubwrens, thornbills, etc.), and [[Maluridae]] (Australian fairy-wrens) in a large [[Meliphagoidea]] superfamily.<ref>Barker, F.K., Cibois, A., Schikler, P., Feinstein, J., and Cracraft, J (2004) Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation. ''Proceedings Natl. Acad. Sci., USA'' '''101''' 11040-11045</ref>\n\nThe tawny-crowned honeyeater is found from the [[Northern Rivers|North Coast]] of New South Wales through to the [[Eyre Peninsula]] in South Australia, as well as in Victoria and Tasmania. It also occurs in southwest Western Australia from [[Israelite Bay, Western Australia|Israelite Bay]] westwards. Its natural habitat is low shrubland and heath.<ref name=Ber93/>\n\nThe breeding season may take place from June to December. The bulky [[cup nest|cup-shaped nest]] is made of bark, grass, and even seaweed, and lined with softer material such as fur or wool. It is hidden among shrubby vegetation. The [[avian clutch size|clutch size]] is usually two or three, and occasionally four. Measuring 21 x 14&nbsp;mm, the oval eggs are beige, with buff or pink-tinged splotches.<ref name=Ber93>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = G  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | pages = 324 |isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"240\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Tawny-crowned honeyeater.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q775477}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, tawny-crowned}}\n[[Category:Meliphagidae|tawny-crowned honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1837|tawny-crowned honeyeater]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tawny-crowned_honeyeater"}
{"title_page": "Vice-admiral of the red", "text_new": "{{short description|Rank of the navy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of Red 1805 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of Red (1805-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the Red\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAR \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Admiral of the blue]]\n| lower rank     = [[Vice-admiral of the White|Vice-Admiral of the White]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the Red''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Admiral of the Blue (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%20the%20ranks%20of%20rear%20admiral%2C%20vice%20admiral%20and%20admiral%20of%20the%20fleet%20are%20sometimes%20considered%20generically%20to%20be%20admirals&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence fourth; after 1805 it was the fifth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank. (pictured opposite is the command flag for an Vice-Admiral of the Red).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. The rank of [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] was formally introduced in 1688.<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the White was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Admiral of the Blue (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.  From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence fourth; after 1805 it was the fifth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Services |first1=Library |title=Information sheet no 055 Squadron colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Order of precedence Admirals of the Colour==\nThe Navy was divided into three squadrons Red, White and Blue in order of seniority. Admirals were appointed to these squadrons and therefore their rank and squadron split the seniority originally into 9 bands then later 10 with \u2018Admiral of the Fleet' as senior to all others..<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1805 to 1864:\n# [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n# [[Admiral of the Red|Admiral of the Red Squadron]] (rank created in 1805)\n# [[Admiral of the White|Admiral of the White Squadron]] \n# [[Admiral of the Blue|Admiral of the Blue Squadron]] \n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron'''\n# [[Vice-admiral of the White|Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Vice-Admiral of the Blue|Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-admiral of the red|Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the White|Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the Blue|Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1688 to 1805:\n\n# Admiral of the Fleet, (rank created in 1688)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron'''\n# Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nAdmirals without an appointment were colloquially referred to as Yellow Admirals. Ships of the Royal Navy flew the Ensign that coincided with the squadron of their commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Former command flag 1625 to 1805==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag Vice Admiral of the Red 1702 to 1805.png|Vice Admiral of the Red Squadron command flag 1625 to 1805.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n# [[List of command flags of the Royal Navy]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n# Perrin, W. G. (William Gordon) (1922). \"Flags of Command: Admirals Flags\". British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device. Cambridge, England: Cambridge : The University Press.\n# Squadron Colours\" (2014), (PDF). National Museum of the Royal Navy.\n\n[[Category:Military ranks of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy appointments]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rank of the navy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of Red 1805 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of Red (1805-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the Red\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAR \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Admiral of the blue]]\n| lower rank     = [[Vice-admiral of the White|Vice-Admiral of the White]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the Red''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Admiral of the Blue (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%20the%20ranks%20of%20rear%20admiral%2C%20vice%20admiral%20and%20admiral%20of%20the%20fleet%20are%20sometimes%20considered%20generically%20to%20be%20admirals&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence fourth; after 1805 it was the fifth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank. (pictured opposite is the command flag for an Vice-Admiral of the Red).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. The rank of [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] was formally introduced in 1688.<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the White was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Admiral of the Blue (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers currently holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be admirals.  From 1688 to 1805 this rank was in order of precedence fourth; after 1805 it was the fifth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Services |first1=Library |title=Information sheet no 055 Squadron colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Order of precedence Admirals of the Colour==\nThe Navy was divided into three squadrons Red, White and Blue in order of seniority. Admirals were appointed to these squadrons and therefore their rank and squadron split the seniority originally into 9 bands then later 10 with \u2018Admiral of the Fleet' as senior to all others..<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1805 to 1864.:\n# [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n# [[Admiral of the Red|Admiral of the Red Squadron]] (rank created in 1805)\n# [[Admiral of the White|Admiral of the White Squadron]] \n# [[Admiral of the Blue|Admiral of the Blue Squadron]] \n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron'''\n# [[Vice-admiral of the White|Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Vice-Admiral of the Blue|Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-admiral of the red|Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the White|Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the Blue|Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1688 to 1805.:\n\n# Admiral of the Fleet, (rank created in 1688)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron'''\n# Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nAdmirals without an appointment were colloquially referred to as Yellow Admirals. Ships of the Royal Navy flew the Ensign that coincided with the squadron of their commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Former command flag 1625 to 1805==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag Vice Admiral of the Red 1702 to 1805.png|Vice Admiral of the Red Squadron command flag 1625 to 1805.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n# [[List of command flags of the Royal Navy]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n# Perrin, W. G. (William Gordon) (1922). \"Flags of Command: Admirals Flags\". British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device. Cambridge, England: Cambridge : The University Press.\n# Squadron Colours\" (2014), (PDF). National Museum of the Royal Navy.\n\n[[Category:Military ranks of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy appointments]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrder of precedence Admirals of the Colour", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vice-admiral_of_the_red"}
{"title_page": "Jayantha Perera", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = [[Admiral]]\n| name              = Jayantha Perera\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = Vice Admiral Satish Soni presents ENC crest to Vice Admiral Jayantha Perera.jpeg\n| image_size    = 300px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = <span style=\"font-size:88%\">Perera (left)</span>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|07|11}}<ref name=\"chart\">{{cite news|title=Travis Sinniah to have shortest tenure?|url=http://www.srilankamirror.com/news/5106-travis-sinniah-to-have-shortest-tenure|accessdate=25 October 2017|agency=Sri Lanka Mirror|publisher=srilankamirror.com|date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_place   = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance= [[Sri Lanka]]\n| rank          = [[Admiral]]\n| branch=[[Image:Naval Ensign of Sri Lanka.svg|25px]] [[Sri Lanka Navy]] \n| serviceyears  = 1978 - 2015\n| servicenumber = NRX 0140<ref name=\"chart\"/>\n| unit          = \n| commands      = [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lanka Navy]]<br> Chief of Staff<br> Western Naval Command<br> Southern Naval Command<br> \n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = [[File:Rana Wickrama Padakkama Bar.png|20px]] [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]]<br> [[File:Vishista_Seva_Vibhushanaya_bar.GIF|20px]] [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]<br> [[File:Uttama Seva Padakkama Bar.gif|20px]] [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = Presidential Advisor on Maritime Affairs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/83629/admiral-jayantha-perera-appointed-advisor-to-president|title=Admiral Jayantha Perera appointed Advisor to President|website=Dailymirror.lk|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n| signature     = \n| website       =\n| module        = \n}}\n\n[[Admiral]] (retired) '''Jayantha Perera''' [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama|RWP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[National Defence University, Pakistan|ndu]], [[Psc (Military)#Sri Lanka|psc]] was the 19th [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]].\n\n==Education and career==\nEducated at [[Thurstan College]], [[Colombo]], Perera enlisted in the [[Sri Lanka Navy]] on 23 August 1978.<ref name= \"sundaytimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/140629/news/vice-admiral-jayantha-perera-19th-navy-commander-on-july-1-105120.html|title=Vice Admiral Jayantha Perera 19th Navy Commander on July 1|website=Sundaytimes.lk|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref><ref name= \"highbeam\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-3011903131.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416012607/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-3011903131.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 April 2018|title=Rear Admiral Jayantha Perera Appointed Navy Chief of Staff|website=Highbeam.com|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> Completing basic training at the [[Naval and Maritime Academy]] in [[Trincomalee]] in 1979, he went on to specialize in gunnery at [[INS Dronacharya]] in [[Kochi]], [[India]].<ref name= \"sundaytimes\" /> In 1996, he completed an [[MSc]] in Defense Studies at the [[University of Madras]], and would earn another [[MSc]] in Defense & Strategic Studies at the [[National Defence University, Pakistan|National Defence University]] in [[Islamabad]].<ref name= \"sundaytimes\" />\n\nPerera commanded the SLN flagship [[SLNS Sayura]] in the 2000-2003 period and was the [[Flag officer]] commanding the naval fleet from 2006 to 2007 based at [[Trincomalee]], simultaneously serving as Deputy Area Commander for the Eastern Command.<ref name= \"sundaytimes\" /><ref name= \"dailynews\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2013/07/05/sec01.asp|title=Rear Admiral Jayantha Perera appointed Navy Chief of Staff|website=Dailynews.lk|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> Other staff appointments he has held at various times include:\n*Director Naval Operations and Naval Special Forces\n*Director Naval Weapons\n*Deputy Director of Naval Intelligence\n*Deputy Director of Naval Training\n*Media Spokesman for the SLN\n*Principal Staff Officer to the Chief of Defence Staff\nHe has held, in order, the SLN's Southern and Western Commands in the 2007-2009 period, and following a brief three-month stint as the navy's Director General- Services, was appointed Director General- Operations- a position he occupied until July 2013, when he was appointed Chief of Staff of the [[Sri Lanka Navy|SLN]].<ref name= \"sundaytimes\" /><ref name= \"highbeam\" /><ref name= \"dailynews\" /> He was awarded the [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]] the same year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://navaltoday.com/2013/07/17/sri-lanka-naval-personnel-awarded-gallantry-medals|title=Sri Lanka: Naval Personnel Awarded Gallantry Medals|website=Navaltoday.com|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Navy]] on 1 July 2014, and was promoted to the rank of [[admiral]] on his retirement from duty on 9 July 2015.<ref name= \"sundaytimes\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://navaltoday.com/2014/07/01/19th-commander-of-sri-lanka-navy-appointed/|title=19th Commander of the Sri Lanka Navy appointed|website=Navaltoday.com|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=Commander_of_the_Navy_Vice_Admiral_Jayantha_Perera_promoted_to_the_rank_of_Admiral_20150710_01|title=Commander of the Navy, Vice Admiral Jayantha Perera promoted to the rank of Admiral|website=Defence.lk|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=Vice_Admiral_Ravindra_Wijegunaratne_assumes_duties_as_the_20th_Commander_of_the_Nav_20150711_01|title=Vice Admiral Ravindra Wijegunaratne assumes duties as the 20th Commander of the Navy|website=Defence.lk|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n<br>\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jayanath Colombage]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Navy]]|years=July 2014 - July 2015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ravindra Wijegunaratne]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jayanath Colombage]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chief of Staff of the Sri Lankan Navy|years=July 2013 - July 2014}}\n{{s-aft| after = [[Ravindra Wijegunaratne]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Navy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perera, Jayantha}}\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Navy]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan admirals]]\n[[Category:Naval and Maritime Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = [[Admiral]]\n| name              = Jayantha Perera\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = Vice Admiral Satish Soni presents ENC crest to Vice Admiral Jayantha Perera.jpeg\n| image_size    = 300px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = <span style=\"font-size:88%\">Perera (left)</span>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|07|11}}<ref name=\"chart\">{{cite news|title=Travis Sinniah to have shortest tenure?|url=http://www.srilankamirror.com/news/5106-travis-sinniah-to-have-shortest-tenure|accessdate=25 October 2017|agency=Sri Lanka Mirror|publisher=srilankamirror.com|date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_place   = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance= {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n| rank          = [[Admiral]]\n| branch=[[Image:Naval Ensign of Sri Lanka.svg|25px]] [[Sri Lanka Navy]] \n| serviceyears  = 1978 - 2015\n| servicenumber = NRX 0140<ref name=\"chart\"/>\n| unit          = \n| commands      = [[Commander of the Navy (Sri Lanka)|Comman